{
  "global": "Fix the seaborn legend formatter to retrieve and incorporate the ScalarFormatter offset value so that large-number legend labels display the correct multiplicative offset (e.g., ×10⁶) instead of raw unscaled tick values.",
  "subtasks": [
    {
      "subtask": "Locate and understand the legend label generation code in seaborn/_core/scales.py around lines 377-382 where ScalarFormatter is applied to produce legend tick labels",
      "atomics": [
        "Read seaborn/_core/scales.py lines 360-400 to identify where ScalarFormatter is instantiated and used to format legend labels",
        "Identify the exact call site where formatter labels are extracted (e.g., format_ticks or similar) without calling formatter.get_offset()",
        "Trace how the resulting label list is passed into legend construction to understand where offset must be injected"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Understand the ScalarFormatter offset API and determine the correct strategy for incorporating the offset into the legend",
      "atomics": [
        "Inspect matplotlib ScalarFormatter.get_offset() to understand the string it returns (e.g., '×10⁶') and when it is non-empty",
        "Check rcParams 'axes.formatter.useoffset' and 'axes.formatter.offset_threshold' to understand conditions under which an offset is generated",
        "Decide whether to append the offset to the legend title string or prepend/append it to each individual label string, preferring title annotation as matplotlib axes do"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Implement the fix: after generating formatter labels, call formatter.get_offset() and, if non-empty, append the offset string to the legend title",
      "atomics": [
        "After the block that calls formatter to produce label strings in seaborn/_core/scales.py, add a call to formatter.get_offset() and store the result",
        "If the offset string is non-empty, modify the legend title by appending the offset (e.g., 'body_mass_mg\\n×10⁶') so users see the scaling factor",
        "Ensure the code path is guarded so it only applies when get_offset() returns a non-empty string, leaving small-number legends unchanged"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Write a regression test that reproduces the original bug and verifies the fix",
      "atomics": [
        "Create a test that builds a Plot with a numeric variable whose values are in the 1e6 range, triggering ScalarFormatter offset",
        "Assert that the rendered legend title or label text contains the expected offset string (e.g., '1e6' or '×10⁶') and that legend labels show values without the full unscaled magnitude",
        "Run the existing seaborn test suite to confirm no regressions in legend formatting for normal-range numeric scales"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "global_atomics": [
    "Verify the fix works for both the so.Plot / so.Dot path and the scatterplot path if they share the same ScalarFormatter legend code path",
    "Run ruff/flake8 and mypy on the modified seaborn/_core/scales.py to ensure no style or type errors were introduced"
  ],
  "gold_actions": {
    "global": "In seaborn/_core/scales.py, after extracting label strings from ScalarFormatter, call formatter.get_offset() and append the returned offset string to the legend title when it is non-empty.",
    "subtasks": [
      {
        "subtask": "Read seaborn/_core/scales.py lines 360-410 and identify the exact lines where ScalarFormatter produces legend labels without offset",
        "atomics": [
          "Open seaborn/_core/scales.py and read the _ContinuousBase or Continuous scale class, specifically the block around line 377 that calls ScalarFormatter and collects formatted tick strings",
          "Confirm that formatter.get_offset() is never called in this block, causing the offset multiplier to be silently dropped",
          "Trace the label list to the legend-building call (e.g., _legend_artist or similar) to find where the title string originates"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Verify ScalarFormatter.get_offset() returns the offset string (e.g., '$\\times10^{6}$') for values in the 1e6 range under default rcParams",
        "atomics": [
          "Write a small inline check: instantiate ScalarFormatter, call set_lims and format ticks for values like [2000000, 3000000, 4000000], then call get_offset() and inspect the return value",
          "Confirm that under default rcParams (useoffset=True, offset_threshold=4), values of order 1e6 produce a non-empty offset string",
          "Confirm that for small values (e.g., 1–10), get_offset() returns an empty string, so the guard condition is correct"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Edit seaborn/_core/scales.py: after the formatter label extraction block, call get_offset() and append its value to the legend title string",
        "atomics": [
          "Immediately after the list comprehension or loop that builds label strings from ScalarFormatter, add: offset = formatter.get_offset()",
          "Add a conditional: if offset: title = f'{title}\\n{offset}' (or equivalent) where title is the legend variable name string passed to the legend builder",
          "Ensure the modified title is passed into whatever function or dict constructs the legend, replacing the unmodified title"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Add a pytest test in tests/_core/test_scales.py (or appropriate file) that asserts the offset appears in the legend title for large-range numeric data",
        "atomics": [
          "Create test_large_range_legend_title() that constructs a Continuous scale with tick values [2000000, 3000000, 4000000] and calls the legend label generation code path",
          "Assert that the returned legend title string contains the offset token (e.g., assert '1e6' in title or assert '×' in title)",
          "Run pytest tests/_core/test_scales.py -v and confirm the new test passes and no existing tests fail"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "global_atomics": [
      "Test both so.Plot(penguins, pointsize='body_mass_mg').add(so.Dot()) and sns.scatterplot with size='body_mass_mg' to confirm both legend rendering paths display the offset correctly",
      "Run uv run ruff check --fix seaborn/_core/scales.py && uv run mypy seaborn/_core/scales.py and resolve any reported issues before finalizing the patch"
    ]
  }
}
